# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We know that in bst the two nodes p and q can lie on either sides of root or at same side of the root. Therefore, the lowest common ancestor will be the node that splits both the nodes on either side of the bst or the node which itself is either of p or q.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/13eefeec-a9e2-4ac6-a036-1426669612a5_1691240130.2432892.png)

We know that in bst the two nodes p and q can lie on either sides of root or at same side of the root. For eg in the above example 1, 2 and 8 lie on opposite sides of 6 and thus 6 is LCA(2, 8).

Therefore, we can conclude that lowest common ancestor for two nodes will the node that splits both p and q to either side of itself.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/bf283ff0-c57d-4f15-93c2-0555da122bb4_1691240151.3338797.png)


In example 2, we can see that both nodes p and q do not lie at left nor at right of any node thus, in such case the root is the LCA. this is because if p and q both do not lie on same side then that means that root node is one of the node from p or q. Thus, it becomes LCA.

Therefore, we traverse the bst and move to left or right according to node value until root becomes null or we find the split in paths. Once split in paths is found or node is equal to either p or q then we return that node.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(h) {height of bst}

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(1) {No extra space used}

