solutions.content:
# Intuition
Since the given binary tree is a BST, and we assume `p` and `q` will exist in this BST, the LCA of `p` and `q` actually is the first node that splits `p.val` and `q.val`, i.e. it is either `p.val <= LCA.val <= q.val` or `q.val <= LCA.val <= p.val` (since all `node.val` are unique, in reality there will be at most one "="). In this case, we can simplify this problem to a simple search problem within BST.

Note that if we do not have the constraint "`p` and `q` will exist in this BST", we have to traverse the entire BST to check the existence `p` and `q`. The following "first spliting node" method will not be applicable any more.

# Approach
We can either use recursion or iteration to solve this problem.

---
Recursive approach:
Base case: if the root is null, then return null.
Recursive rule:
- if both `p.val` and `q.val` are smaller than `root.val`, then the LCA must be within the root's left subtree, so we search the root's left child;
- if both `p.val` and `q.val` are greater than `root.val`, then the LCA must be within the root's right subtree, so we search the root's right child;
- otherwise, `root` splits `p` and `q`, so we return root as our result.

---
Iterative approach:
The logic is very similar to recursive approach, but by using iteration, we can avoid using O(h) space on the stack.
So basically we create a pointer starting from `root`. We create a while-loop to search LCA until `root` becomes `null`.
- if both `p.val` and `q.val` are smaller than `root.val`, then the LCA must be within the root's left subtree, so we substitute `root` by its left child and continue the loop;
- if both `p.val` and `q.val` are greater than `root.val`, then the LCA must be within the root's right subtree, so we substitute `root` by its right child and continue the loop;
- otherwise, `root` splits `p` and `q`, so we return root as our result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(h)$$ for both recursive & iterative approach

- Space complexity: $$O(h)$$ for recursive approach, $$O(1)$$ for iterative approach

