solutions.content:
## Basic Idea of the Question
This question is similar to [236. Lowest Common Ancestor of a Binary Tree](https://leetcode.com/problems/lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree/) except that the fact that the tree given to us is actually a Binary Search Tree helps us to find the elements more quickly.

The basic idea is that the Lowest Common Ancestor is a place where the paths from the root to the nodes diverge, or where one of the paths ends and the other continues.
There can be one of three cases:

1. Either one of them is the current subtree's root itself.
2. Or they are in different subtrees.
3. Or they are in the same subtree.

Cases 1 and 2 are our base cases, since here the root will the LCA. Let's consider these one by one to think why that is true.

### Case 1:
If one of the nodes is the root and the other one is one of the children of the root (assuming that the given nodes are not equal), then the Lowest Common Ancestor of these nodes is the node which is equal to the root, since the last common node in the paths from the root to these nodes, is that node. So we return the current root here.

### Case 2:
If the nodes are in different subtrees, then the path from the root of the tree to these nodes, will always diverge at this subtree's root, thus making the current root as the LCA. So we return the current root again.

If both of the nodes are in the same subtree, then that means that we have not found the diverging point yet, so we recurse on whichever subtree they are in.
<br/>
## Approach
Now this is the exact same approach I used in the general question with Binary Trees as well. But here this approach can be made faster, since we can find whether a node exists in a particular subtree in O(1) (which was O(n) in the Binary Trees). We can check this by just comparing the node's value to the value of the root. If it is less than root's value, then the node is in the left subtree, else it is in the right subtree.
We don't have to worry about the grandparent's value, since that would have already been checked in the upper levels.
<br/>
## Code
The code for the above approach can be written as follows:
```
TreeNode *lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode *root, TreeNode *p, TreeNode *q) {
	if(p == root || q == root) return root;
	else if(p->val < root->val) {
		//p is in the left subtree
		if(q->val < root->val) {
			//q is also in the left subtree
			//go left
			return lowestCommonAncestor(root->left, p, q);
		}
		else {
			//q is in the right subtree
			//they are in different subtrees
			//thus root is the LCA
			return root;
		}
	}
	else {
		//p is in the right subtree
		if(q->val > root->val) {
			//q is also in the right subtree
			//go right
			return lowestCommonAncestor(root->right, p, q);
		}
		else {
			//q is in the left subtree
			//root is the LCA
			return root;
		}
	}
}
```

As you can see, this solution is recursive, but since the recursion is only tail recursion (i.e there is only one recursive call per function call), we can easily convert this into iterative solution.

The iterative solution can be written as follows:
```
TreeNode *lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode *root, TreeNode *p, TreeNode *q) {
	while(root != p && root!= q) {
		if(p->val < root->val) {
			if(q->val < root->val) {
				//go left
				root = root->left;
			}
			else {
				//root is the LCA
				return root;
			}
		}
		else {
			if(q->val < root->val) {
				//root is the LCA
				return root;
			}
			else {
				//go right
				root = root->right;
			}
		}
	}
	return root;
}
```

**Time: O(h)** where h is the height of the BST, since in the worst case we would find the LCA at the second last level (when p and q are leaves). In a balanced BST, this will be O(logn), since the height is maintained O(logn) in it.

**Space: O(h)** in the case of the recursive solution (the call stack space), and **O(1)** in the case of the iterative solution.

Feel free to ask any doubts or suggest any corrections/improvements in the comments.
